{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505987"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:38:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:38:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2503"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2503"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.11,0.13,0.07,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2503"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111987"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2503"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2503"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94051"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1170"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2190"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2314"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2352"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45677"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111987"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after being found by police lying in a pool of urine. He has been confused and unable to answer questions, with an uncertain time of onset. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears drowsy and is not oriented to time, place or person. His pulse rate is 70/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 13/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. His pupils are pinpoint. The abdomen is soft and non-tender. There is skin mottling over the back, buttocks, and posterior thighs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin 136 g/L (135-175)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count 9.2 \u00d710\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelets 250 \u00d710\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESodium 136 mmol/L (137-145)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPotassium 6.4 mmol/L (3.5-4.9)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECreatinine 99 \u03bcmol/L (50-100)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECalcium 1.8 mmol/L (2.1-2.55)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECreatine kinase 25,000 U/L (30-200)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELactate dehydrogenase 700 U/L (110-230)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBilirubin 12 \u03bcmol/L (2-24)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlanine aminotransferase 132 U/L (\u0026lt;55)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAspartate aminotransferase 220 U/L (\u0026lt;45)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlkaline phosphatase 56 U/L (30-110)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions is this patient at greatest risk of developing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute kidney injury","Cerebral oedema","Liver failure","Osmotic demyelination syndrome","Disseminated intravascular coagulation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERhabdomyolysis results from skeletal muscle breakdown with release of intracellular contents, often after prolonged immobilisation, drug toxicity, heat illness, or crush injury. Hallmarks include markedly elevated creatine kinase, hyperkalaemia, hypocalcaemia, and a predominant rise in aspartate aminotransferase over alanine aminotransferase due to muscle origin of aspartate aminotransferase. Myoglobin released from damaged muscle can cause pigment nephropathy. Early recognition and aggressive fluid resuscitation reduce complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute kidney injury\u003C/strong\u003E is the greatest near-term risk in severe rhabdomyolysis. Hypovolaemia from third spacing into injured muscle reduces renal perfusion, and filtered myoglobin precipitates in renal tubules causing direct toxicity and obstruction, particularly in acidic urine. The combination of creatine kinase of 25,000 U/L, hyperkalaemia, and hypocalcaemia in this patient supports high risk, even with creatinine still within the reference interval.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral oedema\u003C/strong\u003E is linked to rapid shifts in serum sodium or severe hepatic failure, and is not a typical complication of rhabdomyolysis. This patient has near-normal sodium and no features of raised intracranial pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver failure\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely; although alanine aminotransferase is elevated, the disproportionate rise in aspartate aminotransferase reflects muscle injury rather than primary hepatic dysfunction, and bilirubin and alkaline phosphatase are not suggestive of acute hepatic failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsmotic demyelination syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E occurs after rapid correction of chronic hyponatraemia; sodium here is 136 mmol/L (137-145), so there is no risk scenario for this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisseminated intravascular coagulation\u003C/strong\u003E can complicate severe systemic illness and massive tissue injury, but it is less common in uncomplicated rhabdomyolysis compared with acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rhabdomyolysis from prolonged immobilisation commonly leads to acute kidney injury due to hypoperfusion and myoglobin-mediated tubular toxicity.","Hyperkalaemia, hypocalcaemia, and markedly elevated creatine kinase with predominant AST rise suggest muscle injury rather than primary hepatic pathology."],"references":["Stanley M, Adigun R. Rhabdomyolysis. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448168/","Lima RS, da Silva Junior GB, Liborio AB, Daher Ede F. Acute kidney injury due to rhabdomyolysis. Saudi J Kidney Dis Transpl. 2008;19(5):721-9. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4056317/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94051"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2503"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94051"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-22T16:51:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-22T16:52:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2503"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111987"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":n